## Testing Your Policies

### Manual Testing

```bash
# Test GetObject access
aws s3api get-object \
  --bucket project-bucket \
  --key path/to/file.txt \
  --profile test-role \
  output.txt

# Test ListBucket access
aws s3 ls s3://project-bucket/ --profile test-role

# Test denied action (should fail)
aws s3 rm s3://project-bucket/protected-file --profile test-role
# Should output: permission denied
```

### Using AWS CLI Policy Simulator (Recommended)

```bash
aws iam simulate-principal-policy \
  --policy-source-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/test-role \
  --action-names s3:GetObject s3:PutObject s3:DeleteObject \
  --resource-arns arn:aws:s3:::project-bucket/subfolder/*
```

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Always use specific resource ARNs** - Never use wildcards unless absolutely necessary
2. **Deny before Allow** - Use Deny statements to prevent dangerous operations
3. **Encrypt always** - Add encryption conditions to all PutObject permissions
4. **Audit everything** - Enable CloudTrail and S3 access logging
5. **Review quarterly** - Remove unused permissions regularly
6. **Test in DEV first** - Never apply untested policies to production

